{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CtJu4b5uBZX5DQiq5U5q3n","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for the PR review automation system.\n\n**Behavior 1: The review input is scoped to the lines that changed, not the full content of each modified file.**\n\nThis is about parsing/filtering the diff — checking that the code correctly extracts only changed lines from a diff. This is fundamentally a parsing/algorithm question. The failure mode is: does the diff parsing logic correctly scope to changed lines? This can be tested with a Unit test — given a diff string, does the scoping logic return only the changed lines? No real HTTP, no LLM needed. It's testing a local parsing function.\n\nMOCK-MISS: Single function logic — Unit\n\n\nREAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed, just diff string parsing\nLLM-DEP: No\nMULTI-STEP: No\n\nMinimum level: **Unit**\n\n**Behavior 2: Inline comments are attached to the correct positions in the diff view on the pull request.**\n\nThis involves two layers: the position calculation logic that maps comments to diff locations, and then actually posting those to GitHub's API using their diff position numbering system. The calculation itself can be unit tested, but verifying the comments land in the right spots requires hitting the real GitHub API. The position calculation itself is testable with mocks — if the payload sent to the API has the right position numbers, that catches the failure. GitHub's diff position format is complex, but an in-process mock HTTP client can validate whether the positions are correct without needing real API responses. So this lands on Integration.\n\nFor the behavior about identifying real defects, that's clearly dependent on actual LLM output — running it multiple times could yield different results. This requires Agentic-level testing.\n\nThe last behavior about findings corresponding to inline comments is cut off, but it's likely checking consistency between summary and actual comments. posted — no findings appear in the summary without a matching inline comment.**\n\nThis is about consistency between the summary and inline comments. The failure mode is: the agent generates findings in the summary that don't have corresponding inline comments. This is about the coordination/consistency logic.\n\nCould this be Unit? The logic of \"ensure every summary finding has a corresponding inline comment\" could be a local function. But the failure mode is in how the agent coordinates between posting inline comments and generating the summary. \n\nIf this is deterministic logic (e.g., the code builds the summary from the same data structure that was used to post inline comments), it could be Unit. If it involves the LLM generating the summary independently (which might introduce findings not in the inline comments), it's Agentic.\n\nThe key question is whether the summary gets programmatically built from the inline comments or if the LLM generates it fresh and might hallucinate extra findings. Given that this is described as an automation that creates a top-level PR comment summarizing findings, the LLM is likely involved in generating that summary. So the consistency break could stem from either the LLM adding findings it shouldn't or from a logic gap in the coordination. I'm leaning toward Integration since the test would verify the consistency enforcement works correctly, though LLM behavior could still be the underlying cause.\n\nMinimum level: **Integration**\n\n**Behavior 5: The full sequence — reading the diff, posting inline comments, posting the summary comment — completes correctly for a real pull request without manual intervention.**\n\nThis needs real GitHub API calls and actual LLM invocations across multiple steps in sequence. The behavior is fundamentally about the entire pipeline executing successfully end-to-end with real external services, so this requires System level testing.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the test levels: Unit tests for the diff parsing logic, Integration tests for position calculations and API payloads with mocks, Agentic tests for LLM-based defect identification, another Integration layer for consistency between summary and inline comments, and finally a Workflow test for the complete end-to-end sequence with a real PR.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9884,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9884},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c92fdc4-8161-4e8a-a7dc-5390c8aff0cb","uuid":"32c8ef64-9446-4452-8359-85f8222b1768"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CtJu4b5uBZX5DQiq5U5q3n","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01E4LhzRHKJfjyXusp2MFuuQ","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Review input is scoped to changed lines only, not full file content","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is purely algorithmic — does the diff-parsing logic correctly extract only changed lines (additions/deletions/context) and exclude unchanged file content? This is a local parsing/filtering function. No module handoff is needed to surface the bug. REAL-INFRA: A diff string can be provided as a fixture; no OS, network, or subprocess required. LLM-DEP: No. MULTI-STEP: No. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected — the bug lives entirely in the diffing/scoping logic, not in a module boundary.","test_description":"Feed a synthetic unified diff with multiple hunks (including unchanged lines between hunks) to the scoping function. Assert that the returned input contains only lines prefixed with '+' or '-' (and the minimal context lines the model should see), and contains no lines from unchanged regions of the file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Inline comments are attached to the correct positions in the diff view on the pull request","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the position-calculation logic that maps a finding to a GitHub diff position number (a 1-based line count within the unified diff hunk). This calculation involves multiple modules: diff parser → position mapper → API client. The bug surfaces at the module boundary between position calculation and payload construction. REAL-INFRA: Could an in-process mock HTTP client reproduce the failure? Yes — a mock that records the outgoing request body lets us assert the 'position' field has the correct integer. Real HTTP is not needed to catch wrong position numbers. LLM-DEP: No. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected — the position arithmetic is in-process; a mock HTTP client captures a wrong payload just as well as a real one.","test_description":"Construct a real unified diff string with known hunk structure. Run the full position-mapping + comment-building pipeline against it with a mock HTTP client. Assert that for each finding, the 'position' field in the captured POST /repos/.../pulls/.../comments request body matches the expected diff-position integer computed by hand from the hunk.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Agent identifies at least one real defect in a pull request containing a known introduced bug","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Correctness depends entirely on what the real LLM produces. Running the same diff through the pipeline 100 times may yield different findings; no deterministic mock can assert detection quality. The behavior is explicitly a quality claim ('identifies a real defect') that only a real model call can validate. MOCK-HIDE: A stub LLM would trivially pass by returning a canned finding — hiding any real model degradation. REJECTION-GATE: Integration/System rejected — even if we wire up real GitHub HTTP, a mock LLM always finds the planted bug; that proves nothing about real detection capability. Workflow rejected — a single agentic analysis step is sufficient; no multi-step chaining is required to test detection quality.","test_description":"Create a real (or sandboxed) pull request that introduces a known bug (e.g., off-by-one, missing null check). Run the agent against it with a real LLM call. Assert that at least one returned finding references the file/line range containing the planted bug and describes a plausible defect. Mark the test as non-deterministic / retry-able with a pass threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.15}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Every finding in the top-level summary has a matching inline comment — no orphan summary findings","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the consistency-enforcement logic between the findings data structure and the two posting paths (inline comments vs. summary). This is a multi-module coordination bug: the findings collector, the inline-comment poster, and the summary builder must all operate on the same set. A mock LLM returning a fixed findings list and a mock HTTP client recording posted payloads are sufficient to expose a mismatch. LLM-DEP: If the summary is LLM-generated independently (allowing hallucinated extras), the real failure needs Agentic. However, the minimum testable failure — the code wiring not enforcing consistency — is caught at Integration with deterministic inputs. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic rejected as the minimum because the consistency invariant (same findings list used for both outputs) is in-process logic testable without real LLM variance.","test_description":"Stub the LLM to return a fixed list of N findings. Run the full comment-posting pipeline with a mock HTTP client. Collect all inline comment payloads and the summary comment payload. Assert that every bullet/finding reference in the summary body corresponds to exactly one inline comment in the captured requests, and that no extra findings appear in the summary.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.52,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Full sequence — reading the diff, posting inline comments, posting the summary — completes correctly for a real pull request without manual intervention","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"REAL-INFRA: 'Real pull request' requires real HTTP to GitHub API for both reading (GET diff) and writing (POST comments). In-process fakes hide real API authentication, rate-limiting, and response format issues. LLM-DEP: The pipeline includes a real LLM call to generate findings; deterministic stubs cannot validate end-to-end coherence. MULTI-STEP: The sequence is explicitly multi-step and multi-agent: (1) fetch diff via real GitHub API, (2) LLM analysis producing findings, (3) POST inline comments, (4) POST summary comment — each step's real output feeds the next. A failure at any handoff only surfaces when all steps run with real dependencies. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected — real HTTP alone is insufficient; the behavior's correctness also depends on real LLM output driving the posting steps. Agentic rejected — a single LLM call is not the failure boundary; the end-to-end pipeline coordination across real external services is.","test_description":"Open a real (or dedicated test) GitHub pull request with a known diff. Execute the full automation against it using real credentials and a real LLM. Assert: (a) the PR has at least one new inline review comment in the correct file, (b) a top-level PR comment exists containing a summary, (c) no unhandled exceptions occurred, and (d) the automation exits without requiring user input.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.75}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9884,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9884},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c92fdc4-8161-4e8a-